{"id":"project-LICHEN-l255","title":"oscore_ctx_create_with_eui64 SSN restoration sets seq_initialized without validation","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/oscore/oscore.c
Lines: 719-729

When SSN is restored from NVM, the code marks seq_initialized=true without validating the restored value is safe:

```c
/* Try to restore SSN from NVM if callback is registered */
if (s_nvm_read_cb != NULL) {
    uint32_t stored_ssn;
    ret = s_nvm_read_cb(peer_eui64, &stored_ssn);
    if (ret == 0) {
        ctx_idx = ctx_get_index(ctx);
        if (ctx_idx >= 0) {
            ctx->sender_seq = stored_ssn;
            s_seq_initialized[ctx_idx] = true;  // Marked initialized regardless of value
            LOG_DBG("Restored SSN %u from NVM for peer", stored_ssn);
        }
    }
}
```

Issues:
1. If NVM returns an old/stale value (e.g., from before key rotation), nonces will be reused
2. No validation that stored_ssn hasn't wrapped or is close to exhaustion
3. NVM could be corrupted/attacked to return 0, restarting the sequence

Per RFC 8613 Section 7.5, implementations should persist SSN with a safety margin. The read callback should return SSN + margin, but this is the caller's responsibility with no validation here.

Consider adding:
```c
if (stored_ssn >= UINT32_MAX - OSCORE_SSN_ROTATION_CRITICAL) {
    LOG_WRN("Restored SSN near exhaustion, context needs rotation");
}
```

